INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_2035_L061$$, 2026, $$Communication Security (COMSEC) is critical to maintaining the Army's most sensitive networks in support of secure, seamless, battlefield operations. Without COMSEC products, Warfighter communications
 cannot operate at classification levels of SECRET and TOP SECRET. The COMSEC program consists of three-sub programs: COMSEC Cryptographic Systems (CCS), Army Key Management Infrastructure
 (AKMI), and Next Generation Load Device (NGLD) family of systems. COMSEC enables the Army's Next Generation Command and Control (NGC2) initiative to modernize Command and Control (C2) systems.
 This Program is a critical enabler of the Army Modernization Priorities including Cryptographic Modernization 2 (CM2) addressing current and emerging cyber security threats.

 COMSEC Cryptographic Systems (CCS) procures, fields, and sustains National Security Agency (NSA) products in support of secured, encrypted communications across all echelons of tactical, strategic, and
 enterprise networks. CCS consists of a range of products spanning from high-capacity network encryptors for high-echelon post, camps, and stations, to tactical edge user. CCS prices vary based on network
 bandwidth requirements.

 The Army Key Management Infrastructure (AKMI) develops, procures, and sustains systems that deliver Cryptographic Key and products from the National Security Agency (NSA) Key Management Infrastructure
 (KMI) storefront across all echelons of strategic, tactical, and enterprise networks. These systems provide secure storage, transport and distribution capabilities for NSA certified high-assurance devices and
 are critical to maintaining all high-assurance networks. AKMI includes Management Client (MGC) Nodes, Over the Network Key (OTNK) specification software including the Intermediary Application (iApp),
 Automated Communications Engineering Software (ACES), Simple Key Loader (SKL), and Next Generation Load Device - Small (NGLD-S). The AKMI effort is also slated to support application convergence of
 its current software solutions into the NGC2 architecture.

 The Next Generation Load Device - Medium (NGLD-M) issues, fills, and manages cryptographic key and mission planning products from the National Security Agency (NSA) Key Management Infrastructure
 (KMI) and End-Cryptographic Units (ECUs). The NGLD-M enhances and replaces the capabilities of the legacy product, the Simple Key Loader (SKL), by providing secure, Over-the-Network Keying (OTNK),
 reducing the logistics burden of touching all ECUs across the force. The NGLD-M device is being developed to meet NSA Cryptographic Modernization 2 (CM2) requirements. This effort is an Acquisition
 Category III (ACAT III) Program of Record (POR) and has multi-service and multi-national stakeholder interest. Prior to FY2025, this effort was funded under B96004 Key Management Infrastructure (KMI).
 During June 2024, the NGLD-M program realized a cost and schedule deviation due to National Security Agency (NSA) driven hardware security modifications and integration cost increases by the common
 user interface software developer Naval Information Warfare Center - Pacific (NIWC-P). This resulted in longer developmental efforts and a delay to the projected procurement of the NGLD-M. NGLD-M program
 realized a delay in FY 2025 and procurement efforts started in FY 2026.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Army                                                                                                                      Date: April 2026
