INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1508_L005$$, 2026, $$The purpose of the Practice Bombs budget is to procure a variety of low cost alternative practice bombs to be employed by Navy and Marine Corps Aircraft. Using practice bombs in place of High Explosive (HE)
 live rounds is a cost effective and practical way to train aircrew, maintenance personnel, and ground attack controllers. Practice bombs also provide increased training opportunity on ranges where HE ordnance
 is not permitted. The munitions procured through this PE/BLI are procured by the Joint Munitions Command, the Single Manager for Conventional Ammunition, with the exception of the Laser Guided Training
 Round, which is procured by NAVAIR.

 Specific Products are, but not limited to the MK-76 and BDU-33 small practice bombs which are low cost 25lb tear dropped shaped practice bombs that simulate a MK-82 low drag configuration used by the Navy
 and Marine Corps. The CXU-3A/B signal cartridge (daytime operations) spotting charge is used for visual indication of bomb impact. The MK-82 is a 500lb unguided, low-drag practice bomb. Other full-scale
 inert Practice Bomb variations are the MK-83 1,000lb, MK-84 2,000lb, and BLU-109 2,000lb penetrator. The BLU-137 Inert is a full-scale 2,000lb inert penetrator designed by the USAF to improve survivability
 of the BLU-109 and may be used as a suitable substitute. Inert General Purpose Bomb cases are filled with an inert material and have the same weight, size, center of gravity and ballistics of the live bomb
 configurations.

 The Laser Guided Training Round (LGTR) simulates Laser Guided Weapons and provides a low cost alternative to the use of full scale munitions. The LGTR is capable of replicating the Paveway II laser Guided
 Bomb and is suitable for deployment from select Navy and Marine Corps aircraft. The round allows the aviator to exercise the coordination between the aircrew and the laser designator and to emulate delivery
 options and multi-aircraft tactics. The development and retention of this skill set is extensive and the LGTR provides the capability to exercise the system in a cost effective manner.

 The Practice Bombs budget also funds miscellaneous items including but not limited to low cost items such as M70 series cables, MK-89 adapters, lanyards, lugs, nose plugs, inert fill material, control surfaces,
 bands, strakes, aero panels, dunnage, packaging and containers required for assembly and shipment of an inert practice bombs.

 The Product Improvement Program funds efforts to investigate and incorporate design changes to address manufacturing, production and technology insertions that improve practice stores platform integration,
 system reliability, obsolescence, and producibility. Funding may be used to address Production Improvements to outpace the evolving enemy threats/countermeasures to meet warfighter demand.

 The demand for practice bombs correlates to the Training & Readiness (T&R) requirements for both aviation and ground communities. Each T&R syllabus prescribes a minimum number of "live drops" which can
 be satisfied with practice ordnance. The release of practice ordnance as part of realistic and tactical training scenarios provides increased safety, readiness, and combat effectiveness for aircrew and ground
 controllers alike.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
