INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3010_L038$$, 2027, $$The Bomber Tactical Data Link (TDL) will provide low latency, jam-resistant situational awareness and command/control needed to support in-theater operations/missions via a Line-of-Sight (LOS) Link 16
 capability. The program consists of integrating an existing off-the-shelf Link 16 terminal into the B-52. Integration includes Group A wiring, rack, and antennas, along with the Group B blanking unit and notch filter
 Line Replaceable Units (LRU). Multi-Functional Information Distribution System Joint Tactical Radio System (MIDS-JTRS) terminals will be installed inside Section 41 of the aircraft and two external antennas will
 be mounted on the top and bottom of the fuselage. The TDL terminal and LOS capability will be integrated with the rest of the Combat Network Communications Technology (CONECT) subsystem. Updates to
 Common Link Integration Processing (CLIP) will be required to support both LOS message processing.

 This modification is required for the B-52 fleet of 76 aircraft. This modification includes procurement of 74 contractor provided aircraft kits and 2 Engineering and Manufacturing Development (EMD) kits that will
 be installed via programmed depot maintenance (PDM) and contract field teams (CFT).

 Funds may be used for, but not limited to, all costs needed to procure and field, initiate Depot activation and ICS requirements and resolve emerging and short-notice Diminishing Manufacturing Sources and
 Material Shortages (DMSMS), including Life of Type buys, for both aircraft and associated test, and safety of flight issues. Additionally, funds may accommodate Program Management Administration (PMA) and
 support, rapid technology insertion, and fulfill Federal Aviation Agency (FAA) or other mandates necessary to ensure continued aircrew safety and mission effectiveness. DMSMS efforts include removal of end-
 of-life software/hardware within simulators systems and move to a modular, common open system architecture that is sustainable and cyber-resilient, as well as implement requirements and standards defined
 under the Simulator Common Architecture Requirements and Standards (SCARS) initiative.

 Milestone/Development Status

 Lot 1 Installs began April 2024, however, FY23 funds were used to pay for the installs. Fielding began January 2025.
 Milestone C decision issued May 2023.$$, $$$$, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Air Force                                                                                                                                                 Date: April 2026
