INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1810_L026$$, 2026, $$DIVING AND SALVAGE EQUIPMENT:
 The equipment procured from this Diving and Salvage OPN line item provides critical diving and salvage equipment that enables planned/emergent waterborne submarine/ship repairs, salvage and battle
 damage repair operations, search and recovery to water depths up to 20,000 feet of seawater and Undersea Clandestine Insertion of Special Operations Forces (UCI-SOF) (service common equipment) to keep
 our Navy fleet operational and enable national priority missions. Program objectives are to: (1) provide increased safety for divers, (2) increase underwater ship maintenance capabilities, (3) provide reliable,
 rapid response salvage capability, and (4) reduce diving equipment maintenance costs by standardizing configuration of diving systems in the Fleet.

 FY-27 investment in Diving capability continues to emphasize phased replacement of aging life support equipment including surface-supplied diving helmet upgrades, HP composite flask replacements, SCUBA
 regulators and surface supplied augmented SCUBA sets, an HP Air Compressor, Air Rack Upgrades, Multi-occupant flexible recompression chamber and a Diver Launch and Recovery System. Navy dive
 computers, required by each diver to calculate decompression penalties, will also be procured. This equipment is essential to maintaining diving readiness throughout the Fleet. Additionally, we will make
 investments in new technology equipment that offer capability gains such as Diver Augmented Visual Display (DAVD) 3-D Sonar. These systems will produce a virtual environment in which a diver can operate
 and be directed by topside supervisors to execute salvage, search and recovery and other missions. Lastly, we continue to invest in upgrades to the Navy Experimental Diving Unit, which houses national assets
 such as the Ocean Simulation Facility (OSF). The OSF is a 40+ year old system that permits advanced research and testing of diving technology, diving procedures, human performance, decompression and
 physiology essential to advancing diving capabilities.

 FY-27 investment in Salvage includes a salvage firefighting kit, Deep Drone Upgrade, Lighting Kits, Kerrie Cable Underwater Cutting System, Salvage BDR Material Kit, Salvage Roller Bags, a Full Ocean Depth
 Remotely Operated Vehicle (ROV) and a Full Ocean Depth Line Spooler; all will be used for ship salvage. In Underwater Ship Husbandry (UWSH) we continue investments in cofferdam systems (4 standard and
 1 complex), surface ship support systems, video/camera equipment, UWSH Storage and Shipping Containers, a pier-side support van, a propeller system repair kit, power tools, rigging systems, and a submarine
 support system. Underwater Ship Husbandry investments continue to produce significant returns on investment by eliminating the need for emergent dry dockings, thereby returning ships to service faster and
 less expensive than traditional shipyard availabilities.

 FY-27 investment in Naval Special Warfare Service-Common Equipment provides diving support equipment to include SCUBA diving systems, ROV systems, and MK25 replacements.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
